"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-what-to-watch-paris-olympics-july-30-us-womens-gymnastics\", \"text\": \"Day 4 of the Olympics is here. We will say hello to one sport (3x3 basketball), and goodbye to another (rugby sevens), as the Games roll on. Tuesday has a few high-interest events, so once again I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m here to help you figure out what you need to watch.  To recap all the action, I suggest you subscribe toSports Illustrated\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Daily Ringspodcast. Dan Gartland and I are having a lot of fun taping every night, and new episodes have been published before NBC\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s prime-time coverage is even over.  Here\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s what I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be watching Tuesday, July 30.  This is not a comprehensive list;visit Olympics.comfor a full schedule. All events will stream live on Peacock. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll also be tweeting out a schedule of medal events, Team USA games and other favorites each day.  My Day 4 Olympics viewing guide! Let us have ourselves a Tuesday#Paris2024pic.twitter.com/3qaOhU8Ung  The women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s team final is always one of the marquee events of the Games, and Team USA is favored to take the gold. The U.S. has medaled in seven straight Olympics, following up gold in 2012 and \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009916 with a silver in Tokyo. Simone Biles, Suni Lee and Jordan Chiles are all back from the team that took silver three years ago.  Biles\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s health is the biggest question going into the event, after she aggravated acalf injuryduring qualifying. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be worth keeping an eye on how much that might hamper her in the team final and whether any issues might linger when she competes for individual medals later on in Paris.  The action gets underway at 12:15 p.m. ET.  If you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve been watching 5-on-5 hoops and wishing there was even more basketball in the Olympics, you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re in luck. 3x3 is back for a second time after it was introduced to the Olympic program in Tokyo. These are half-court games, played for either 10 minutes or up to 21 points by ones and twos. They\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll play outdoors on a surface that looks like a blacktop, under a tent.  Both U.S. teams will be in action Tuesday, with the women taking on Germany at 11:30 a.m. ET and the men facing Serbia at 4:35 p.m. ET.  Both teams also feature recognizable names. For the men: 2011 Naismith Player of the Year (and six-year NBA vet) Jimmer Fredette; Canyon Barry, son of Hall of Fame forward Rick Barry; former Princeton forward Kareem Maddox; and Florida Southern alum Dylan Travis. For the women: former Louisville/LSU star Hailey Van Lith (who has now transferred to TCU), three-time WNBA all-star Dearica Hamby, two-time WNBA all-star Rhyne Howard and Cierra Burdick, who last played in the league in 2021.  The good news is that USA women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s rugby won a quarterfinal match against Great Britain Monday, making this the furthest either U.S. team has advanced since rugby sevens became an Olympic sport in 2016. The bad news is their semifinal will be against a New Zealand team that has won its first four contests by an aggregate score of 169\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009324.\\u00c2  But if the U.S. can pull off the upset at 9:30 a.m. ET, the team will play for gold at 1:45. If New Zealand\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s dominant run continues, the U.S. will still get to play for bronze at 1:00 p.m. Either way, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s worth checking out the rugby action on its last day in these Olympics.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Mitch Goldich is a senior editor for Sports Illustrated, mostly focused on the NFL. He has also covered the Olympics extensively and written on a variety of sports since joining SI in 2014. His work has been published by The New York Times, Baseball Prospectus and Food & Wine, among other outlets. Goldich has a bachelor\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from Lehigh University and a master\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from the Medill School at Northwestern University. He is a Philly native, now living in Boston, and he invented and popularized the octopus, when the same player scores a touchdown and the ensuing two-point conversion.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"